column285: Volume and pollution
Too many individual septic systems, drought, increased population

column17: I am still in the Bozeman area off and on, but am living mostly in Dillon now.  I would love to return next year but unsure if it will work out logistically!
column40: I think they have been doing a fantastic job and always enjoy monitoring with Gallatin Stream Teams!  I do not have any suggestions for improvement at this time.
column52: As a returning volunteer, and working professionally in the natural sciences / water rights, I have found the current training method of online videos / review paired with a shorter field session ideal, particularly to fit in with my busy schedule. However, this does require more self-guiding/initiative to make sure you are getting the proper training. I could see an option for a more intensive day training session, more like was done prior to COVID, being beneficial for first time volunteers. However, this would put a larger burden on the organizers, and I do not think is necessary to obtain a well-trained volunteer pool.
column285: I think the development of the Gallatin Valley is the biggest water quality issue we are facing and will face in the coming years. Changing land use patterns from ag to more residential / commercial uses will impact non-points source pollution and have the potential to alter both the physical and chemical nature of the watershed.

column40: I think it would be good if at the training sessions the volunteers are told what the time commitment will be. I didn't realize it would take most of the day. The timing worked out for me, but it caught me by surprise that it was an all day enterprise.
column52: I know it would require more time from the staff, but I think two training sessions would be better, to allow for reinforcement and development of new skills. My first outing as a trained volunteer was almost two months after my training day, and by that time I felt I had not retained as much from the training as I would have liked.
column285: From what I have learned this season, it seems that runoff from home septic systems poses a serious problem to the local watershed.
Elevated nitrate levels, dewatering, elevated temperatures.
The input of nutrients from agriculture, septic and waste water is the biggest issues dfacing the Gallatin right now.

column40: No, was a great program and hope to do it again in the future!
No
column285: Drought as a consequence of climate change

column40: they do a really great job on all aspects that I have experienced; organized, friendly, casual yet serious, educational yet fun, snacks, etc.
column52: see previous comment about their excellent work and organization
column285: Ughhhhhh is the largest issue stormwater runoff (that is polluted) due to the rapidly growing population and construction and pavementization of the hillslopes here? Or, is it all the dog poop in "biodegradeable" bags littering the trails adjacent to streams, inputting organics? Or, is it "traditional" stuff like the Milltown superfund residue? I'm not sure which. No matter what, it's due to humans being selfish, entitled, and probably also ignorant.

column40: N/A
column285: In the Rattlesnake Creek there isn't any large water quality issues. I found that it was a very healthy stream that has had restoration work done on it for years.
column328: I thought it was very fun and educational. Additionally the folks at WEN are awesome! They are super friendly, knowledgeable, and very easy-going. I look forward to volunteering with them again in the future.

column328:
I think this is a well designed survey though both lengthy and somewhat slanted toward assisting solely MSU.  I am ok by this since assisting our higher ed system is a sound watershed group pursuit.  I believe however that MSU could do more to connect with watershed groups.  Say, if MSU could offer technical speakers for watershed group meetings.  It may increase MSU positive visibility.  Carbon County and others in the State are higher education deserts and without higher ed outreach, it could remain that way.   Maybe start by sending watershed groups a roster of technical speakers willing to Zoom or travel, and we would very gladly consider them for our educational meetings.  As it is, watershed groups really have no table of contents to the MSU technical encyclopedia.   

The positive point is that it appears both sides of this survey need data, and I am sure we can jointly work to improve the exchange.  Very best to you and thanks for the opportunity to provide both data and opinion.
